# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydro-québec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] The **2008 Quebec general election** was held in the Canadian province of Quebec on December 8, 2008.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] The 2008 election also marked the first time that Québec solidaire won a seat.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] Charest called the election on November 5, saying he needed a "clear mandate" and a majority to handle the economic storm.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] He was criticized, however, by the Parti Québécois and the Action démocratique du Québec for calling a snap election to get a majority when they were willing to work with him to fix the economy.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] Most notably, the election was marked by a significant collapse in support for the ADQ.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] Formerly a relatively minor party, the ADQ had attracted significant protest support in the 2007 election, beating the Parti Québécois to Official Opposition status.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] In 2008, however, the party's support dropped back to approximately 15 per cent of the popular vote, roughly the same range of support the party attracted before 2007.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] As a result of this loss of support, Mario Dumont announced in his concession speech that he would step down as party leader.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] Both Marois and Dumont called upon Charest, a former leader of the federal Progressive Conservatives, to clarify where he stood on the coalition and on Harper's use of anti-sovereigntist rhetoric in the dispute.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p01] Charest emphasized that the Bloc MPs had been legitimately elected by Quebecers, and stated that "I live in a society in which people can be sovereigntists or federalists, but they respect each other.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p02] "Change" refers to change from previous election.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p02] All parties with more than 1% of the vote are shown individually.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p02] Independent candidates and other minor parties are aggregated separately.
[src:hydro-québec/2008-quebec-general-election-p02] Parties are presented in the order shown on EQ data.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] A long-time opposition leader, Wade ran for president four times, beginning in 1978, before he was finally elected in the year 2000.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He won re-election in 2007 with a majority in the first round, but was defeated in the second round in 2012 in a controversial bid for a third term.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade was born in Kébémer, Senegal, on 29 May 1926 into a Wolof family from Gandiol and Waalo.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Officially, he was born in 1926, although some claim he was born several years earlier, and the record-keeping of the time is not considered particularly reliable.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He studied and taught law at the Lycée Condorcet in France.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He holds two doctorates in law and economics.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He was also dean of the law and economics faculty at the University of Dakar in Senegal.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] At a summit of the Organization of African Unity in Mogadishu in 1974, Wade told President Léopold Sédar Senghor that he wanted to start a new party, and Senghor agreed to this.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The party—initially intended as a Labour party—adopted liberalism in 1976 due to the introduction of a law permitting the existence of only three parties with three distinct ideologies, two of which were taken by other parties (liberalism was therefore the only remaining option).
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade first ran for President in February 1978 against Senghor, taking 17.38% of the vote.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Senghor gave Wade the nickname "Diombor" (Wolof for hare).
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Also in 1978, Wade was elected to the National Assembly, where he served until 1980.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade attracted international attention in the wake of Senghor's announcement in late 1980 that he would resign; as the Secretary General of the PDS, he issued a statement denouncing the process and calling instead for the army to oversee a new set of elections.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Subsequently he ran in the presidential elections of 1983 and 1988, taking second place each time, behind Senghor's successor Abdou Diouf.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Following the 1988 election, he was arrested due to protests against the results and received a suspended sentence.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Subsequently he went to France, but returned in 1990.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In April 1991, Wade and four other PDS members joined a national unity government together with the ruling Socialist Party (PS); Wade became Minister of State without portfolio.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In October 1992, he and the other PDS ministers quit the government due to complaints about the manner in which the PS was said to control the government.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In the February 1993 presidential election, Wade again took second place, with 32% of the vote, behind Diouf, who won with 58%.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Following the May 1993 killing of Constitutional Council Vice-President Babacar Sèye, Wade, along with other PDS leaders, faced police questioning.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] On 1 October, Wade, his wife, and two PDS members of the National Assembly (Abdoulaye Faye and Ousmane Ngom), were charged with complicity in the murder, although they were not held in custody or put on trial.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Following riots in February 1994, Wade was arrested along with many others for allegedly threatening state security.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The charge of complicity in Sèye's murder was dismissed in May 1994, and Wade and his co-defendants began a hunger strike on 30 June.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He and his co-defendants were released on 4 July, and the remaining charges were dismissed on 30 August 1994.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade rejoined the government as Minister of State in March 1995, but he and the other PDS ministers left again in March 1998.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Although he was elected to the National Assembly in the February 1998 parliamentary election, he announced his resignation from the National Assembly in late July 1998, saying that there were "enough deputies to do the job in my place".
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade subsequently spent a year in France, returning to Senegal in October 1999.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In the first round of the 2000 presidential election, held on 27 February, he again took second place, receiving 31% of the vote, but for the first time, Diouf did not win a first round majority, and consequently a second round was held on 19 March.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade won this round with 58.49% of the vote, having received the support of candidates from the first round, including third place candidate Moustapha Niasse.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade became President on 1 April 2000 and appointed Niasse as his Prime Minister shortly afterwards.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade initially cohabited with the PS, which held a majority in the legislature until the PDS and its allies (the Sopi Coalition) won a majority in the April 2001 parliamentary election.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] A new constitution was adopted in 2001, reducing presidential terms to five years following the completion of Wade's seven-year term in 2007.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In September 2002, Wade received the World Peace Culture Award.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In December 2004, he signed a peace accord with rebels in Casamance after 22 years of war with rebels.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] On 15 October 2006, Wade was nominated as presidential candidate of the PDS for the February 2007 presidential election.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] One of Wade's opponents in this election was his former prime minister Idrissa Seck, who was once considered Wade's protégé, but was arrested in 2005.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Final results released on 11 March 2007, showed Wade winning in the first round with 55.9% of the vote, far ahead of his nearest opponents, Seck with about 15% and Socialist Party leader Ousmane Tanor Dieng with about 13.6%.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Dieng and another opposition candidate, Abdoulaye Bathily, filed appeals regarding the election, but these were rejected by the Constitutional Council.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade was sworn in for his second term on 3 April at the Leopold Sedar Senghor Stadium in Dakar, with many African leaders and about 60,000 spectators in attendance.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The main opposition parties did not accept Wade's 2007 victory and disputed his legitimacy as President; they boycotted elections to the National Assembly and the re-established Senate later in the year.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade conclusively stated in an interview published by *Le Soleil* on 19 May 2008 that there was no longer any possibility of dialogue with the opposition unless it recognized him as the legitimate President.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In March 2008 in the country of Comoros, the island of Anjouan decided to declare independence.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Senegal would send troops to the islands of Comoros.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Comoros, along with multiple African Union countries, would win the invasion.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In July 2008, the National Assembly approved a constitutional amendment increasing the length of the presidential term to seven years, as it was prior to the adoption of the 2001 constitution.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] This extension would not apply to Wade's 2007–2012 term, but Minister of Justice Madické Niang stressed on this occasion that Wade could potentially run for re-election in 2012 if he was still healthy.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Later, on 17 September 2009, Wade confirmed that he planned to run for a third term in 2012 "if God gives me a long life".
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade, during a 14 July 2011 speech to supporters, used the Wolof phrase "*Ma waxoon waxeet*" ("I said it, I (can) take it back") in explaining his decision to go back on his 2007 pledge not to run for another term.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The phrase subsequently became a popular rallying cry for the anti-Wade opposition.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] On 27 January 2012, he was officially approved by the Constitutional Council to run for a highly controversial third term.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Following this declaration, enraged mobs engaged in violent protests throughout the city.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] After the first round vote, Abdoulaye Wade acknowledged on 27 February 2012 that he had failed to win a majority in the election and would have to face a run-off.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He subsequently lost the second round of voting, held on 25 March 2012, to the opposition candidate Macky Sall; Sall had received the backing of all of the candidates who were defeated in the first round, and he defeated Wade by a wide margin.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade was internationally praised for his handling of the 2012 presidential election, after congratulating his opponent on his victory and peacefully stepping down.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade's quick concession was praised by the African Union, European Union, United Nations and the United States.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] It was pointed out that the leaders ruling some of Senegal's neighbors (including Guinea, Gambia and Guinea-Bissau) had all previously used the army to maintain their grasp on power.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Because of this, Wade is considered among the rare African leaders who are committed to democracy.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Sall succeeded Wade as President on 2 April 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Following his defeat in the presidential election, Wade remained at the helm of the PDS, even as a number of the party's key figures abandoned it.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He chose not to stand as a candidate for the July 2012 parliamentary election.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The PDS won 12 seats in the vote, marking a tremendous decrease in the party's parliamentary representation, but Wade nevertheless said that he viewed the outcome as encouraging.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He said that, contrary to expectations from some quarters that the PDS would disappear after losing power, it had emerged from the vote as the largest opposition party and the only one with enough seats to form a parliamentary group.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In 2015, despite being close to his 90th birthday, Wade brushed aside suggestions that he should retire, arguing that no credible younger men had come along to succeed him as head of the PDS and that his parents both lived and worked to an advanced age.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In the July 2017 parliamentary election, Wade planned to stand as a candidate at the head of the candidate list of an opposition coalition.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Khalifa Sall, another prominent opposition leader, and his supporters decided to run separately due to disagreement about whether Wade or Sall should receive the top spot on the candidate list.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The divided opposition performed poorly in the election; the coalition backing President Sall won 125 seats, a majority, while Wade's coalition trailed distantly in second place with 19 seats.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] As the top candidate on his coalition's candidate list, Wade himself won a seat, although he had no intention of actually serving as a Deputy; he announced his resignation on 10 September 2017, before the National Assembly even began meeting.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He explained that his purpose in running was merely to support his coalition in the election.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] As of 2019, Wade, although his power has waned somewhat, remains the Secretary-General of the Senegalese Democratic Party (PDS) and still exercises considerable influence within the party.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In the July 2017 parliamentary election, the Wades and the PDS joined a large opposition alliance, in particular with Ousmane Sonko's Pastef and Khalifa Sall's Taxawu Senegaal.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] However, Abdoulaye Wade decided to quickly leave this coalition in September 2021 and recreate a coalition (Wallu Senegal) that brought together roughly the same parties as the winning Manko Wattu coalition formed for the 2017 legislative elections.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] These local elections were a failure for the PDS, which failed to assert itself and found itself marginalized, while at the same time, the coalition led by Ousmane Sonko and Khalifa Sall asserted itself in major cities (Dakar, Ziguinchor, Kaolack).
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The Senegalese government held a series of official events commemorating the event, including a conference on his legacy in June organized in Dakar.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade's presidency was marred by allegations of corruption, nepotism and constraints on freedom of the press and other civil liberties.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He was also criticized for excessive spending on what have been described as "prestige projects".
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] This includes commissioning a 160+ foot bronze statue (the African Renaissance Monument), for which Wade claims he is entitled to 35% of all tourist profits it generates because of the intellectual property for conceiving the idea.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In a parallel controversy, Wade has been criticized by Christian bishops in Senegal for publicly denying the divinity of Jesus Christ, comparing him to the statues found in the African Renaissance Monument, after local imams expressed their opposition to the monument.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He later regretted that his comments had caused religious offense to Christians.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade also received criticism in 2009 for a "goodbye present" he reportedly gave to a departing IMF official after the two had dinner.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] The present turned out to be a bag of money worth almost US$200,000.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Widespread speculation and criticism centered on the possibility that Wade was grooming his son Karim to succeed him.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He went on to say that his son (Karim Wade) "will never accept that Macky Sall is above him", and if slavery still existed today in the country, he would have sold Macky Sall into slavery.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] During his presidency, Wade's land reform laws targeted the land owning Serer community of Senegal - who have inherited their lands since lamanic times, causing many Serer farmers to lose their lands and livelihood.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] His land reform was strongly criticised by certain quarters of the Senegalese media.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Their son, Karim Wade, served as head of the national agency of the Islamic Organization Conference, and subsequently was Minister of State for International Cooperation, Urban and Regional Planning, Air Transport, and Infrastructure.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Their daughter, Sindjely Wade, worked as a Special Assistant to the President and has participated in many Paris-Dakar rallies.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade never renounced his French nationality after the independence of Senegal.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] Wade, a pious Muslim, is a member of the Sufi Mouride brotherhood.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] In March 2012, he announced plans to go to Saudi Arabia for a religious pilgrimage.
[src:hydro-québec/abdoulaye-wade] He turned 100 on 29 May 2026, making him the first state leader in West African history to become a centenarian.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The Algonquins are indigenous to the region.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The first French expeditions were made in 1670 by Radisson as part of the development of the fur trade industry across the Hudson Bay region and through most of the New France colony.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Fort Témiscamingue, located on the east banks of Lake Timiskaming and erected by a French merchant on Anishinaabe lands in 1720, was an important crossroads of the fur trade along the Hudson Bay trading route.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Until 1868, Abitibi was owned by the Hudson's Bay Company; it was then purchased by Canada and became part of the North-West Territories.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] After negotiations with the federal government of Sir Wilfrid Laurier, Abitibi was annexed to the province of Quebec on June 13, 1898, by a federal decree.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] For its part, Témiscamingue had been part of Lower Canada and so was already part of Quebec at Confederation.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The region started to develop during the late 19th and early 20th century, with the development of agriculture and forest industries.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] This began in the southern areas, leading to the foundation of Ville-Marie in 1886 and Témiscaming in 1918.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] However, the greatest wave of colonization occurred between World War I and World War II when a large population came from urban centres due to the effects of the Great Depression.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] In the 1930s, federal and provincial plans such as the Plan Vautrin and the Plan Gordon incited jobless residents to move to undeveloped regions of the province, igniting the beginning of the second colonization flow.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The mining industry, mainly extracting gold and copper, also contributed to the growth of the region when numerous mines were opened.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] New cities were created, such as Rouyn-Noranda in 1926 and Val-d'Or in 1934, and mining is still the backbone of the region's economy nowadays, along with forestry and agriculture.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] As an administrative region, it was created in March 1966, when the entire province was reorganized into 10 regions.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Originally called Nord-Ouest (North-West), the region was renamed to Abitibi-Témiscamingue in 1981.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The Abitibi-Témiscamingue region is the fourth largest region of the province after the Nord-du-Québec, Côte-Nord and Saguenay–Lac-Saint-Jean regions.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Its largest cities are Rouyn-Noranda and Val-d'Or.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The region's landscape features mixed forest to the south across the Témiscamingue area which falls within the St.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Laurence watershed of southern Quebec, while boreal forest covers the Abitibi section further north in the Hudson Bay watershed of northern Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The southern part of the region has a humid continental climate, while the northern part has more of a sub-arctic climate due to its latitude and its proximity to Hudson Bay and the Arctic.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Aiguebelle National Park, the only national park of the region, is located in the centre of the Abitibian region and intends to protect natural heritage.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The region's workforce has one of the highest percentages in the primary sector of any region of Quebec, with nearly one out of six employees working in that sector.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The mining sector is the most important economic activity of the region.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Despite recent declines in workforce, the agriculture and forest industries still contribute significantly to the region's economy.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Economic activities are mainly dedicated to exportation products, and are even closely linked to the Middle North region in its development through hydroelectrical and mining projects, and through exchanges with First Nation northern communities.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Sportive tourism, including winter sports, fishing, hunting and cycling competition, is also a significant economic sector even if negligible by comparison with the industrial sector.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The region is home to one university: UQAT — the Université du Québec en Abitibi-Témiscamingue, which is part of the Quebec public university network.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] UQAT has its main campus at Rouyn-Noranda, a campus dedicated to the first nations at Val-d'Or and several branches in different cities of the region.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The only college in the region is the Cégep de l'Abitibi-Témiscamingue, which has campuses in Amos, Rouyn-Noranda and Val-d'Or, and centres for continuing education in Ville-Marie and La Sarre.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Because of its history and its development, the regional urban planning and the architectural landscape is quite rich in contrasts, showing two main typologies of development.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The agricultural development of northern Abitibi and the northern part of Témiscamingue by a relatively homogeneous population of French Canadian Catholic settlers has introduced a mainly rural land development.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] There, small towns, gravitating around a low density node generally composed of a wooden Roman Catholic church, an elementary school and few houses spread over the territory, according to an orthogonal division on the land, with rectangular parcels.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Those small towns are gravitating themselves around a larger city, as La Sarre, Amos, Macamic and Ville-Marie, where major institutions are established.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] If small towns might seem more or less vernacular, major cities are often more planned and influenced by British urban planning, with sometime an orthogonal grid with lane network.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Because of their central location, main architectural elements are also on those cities.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] For instance, the Cathedral of Sainte-Thérèse d'Avila in Amos is one of the most outstanding architectural element of the region by its size and its Romano-Byzantine style, standing on the upper part of the city, and being at a symbolic central location of the region.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] However, if the cityscapes are often more various, the rural landscape features more local particularities.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The wooden farms and barns built according to many vernacular forms, the fieldstone churches and the wooden houses with locally so-called “Canadian Roof” (steep roof ending with long curved overhang covering a front balcony) are widespread.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The cities of Southern Abitibi and the city of Témiscaming were established later and for industrial concerns, and follow a quite different organization.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] As they grew up often very quickly, the urban planning of these industrial cities is often eclectic.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Bourlamaque mining village is a remarkable example of a borough planned by the mine still visible today in Val-d'Or, with its log houses for workers orderly settled between the mine and the commercial streets, this, at a glace from the foremen’s houses and the hospital.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Noranda was also built according to that scheme, however, the other great example of an industrial town is Témiscaming.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The Témiscaming Garden City plan, designed by Scottish architect Thomas Adams (1871–1940) is a rare example in Quebec of a mono-industrial city where a company planned and endeavoured to grant comfort of its workers.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] There, the dwellings, and even the plan, which follows the shape of the hill, was not alone to grant this comfort, elements as Italian renaissance fountain, landscaping were also included into the cityscape.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Those cities, and many other industrial cities of that part of the region, contrast with the rest of the region, and even generally with the other country regions of Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] As the mining industry was mainly led by owners coming from the anglosphere in the early 20th century, industrial towns even show more similarities with Ontarian industrial cities than other cities in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Added to North American modernity concerns of the 1930s and 1940s, streets are broader and often have numbered names, blocks are orthogonally organized with lanes where boomtown buildings with their peculiar facades are aligned along the main streets while residential buildings take place nearby.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Many mining cities disappeared or have decreased since, but their industrial core often keep being seenable today.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Duparquet and Cadillac, for example, have kept their boomtown appearance, through their street organization, even if the industrial and population exodus gave them a look of oversized village.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Moreover, the multi-cultural settlement of those towns brought many singular architectural elements.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The Russian Orthodox and Catholic Ukrainian churches in Val-d’Or and Rouyn add to the omnipresent architectural eclecticism.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Nowadays, confronted with urban sprawl, those cities tend to develop in a very low density and functionalistic way, as other Quebec and North American cities.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Some great buildings dominate the architectural landscape, as the Rouyn-Noranda campus of the Université du Québec, which could be seen by many aspects as the greatest element of contemporary architecture of the region.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] The region hosts the yearly Tour de l'Abitibi, which first took place in 1969, and which is still the only North American stopover point of the Union Cycliste Internationale Junior World Cup.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] Abitibi-Témiscamingue also hosts a long segment of the Route Verte, the most extensive bicycle and multipurpose recreational trail in North America.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] No professional league sports teams are based in Abitibi.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibi-témiscamingue] It is home to two Quebec Major Junior Hockey League teams: the Val-d'Or Foreurs and the Rouyn-Noranda Huskies.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On 1 July 2012, the company's name was changed to Resolute Forest Products Inc.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] In 2023, the company was acquired by the Paper Excellence Group through its subsidiary, Domtar.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On 29 January 2007, Bowater Inc. and Abitibi-Consolidated announced they would be merging to create AbitibiBowater.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The merger created the third largest pulp and paper company in North America, and the eighth largest in the world.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On 16 April 2009, the company filed for bankruptcy protection in the United States and similar protection under the Companies' Creditors Arrangement Act in Canada, eventually reporting debt of about US$6 billion.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The company won court approval for an injection of $206 million to get it through its financial restructuring in April 2009 and emerged from creditor protection on 9 December 2010.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] AbitibiBowater changed its operating name to Resolute Forest Products on 1 July 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] In a round of market consolidation, a new private company called the Paper Excellence Group acquired Catalyst Paper in 2019, Domtar in 2021 and Resolute in 2023.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] 4. originally named Ontario Paper Company; founded by Robert R.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The Communications, Energy and Paperworkers Union of Canada has been critical of the company's attempts to renegotiate pension contributions with their pension underfunded by approximately $1.9 billion.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On August 29, 2013 a case study examining the use of Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) Controlled Wood system by Resolute was released.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The report concludes that Resolute's improper application of Forest Stewardship Council standards threatens the integrity of the FSC system and brand.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On January 1, 2014, after a successful appeal by the Grand Council of the Crees, three FSC certificates covering more than 8 million hectares of forest were suspended.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] FSC found violations of its principles relating to indigenous Peoples’ rights, environmental impacts, forest benefits, monitoring and assessment, and High Conservation Value forests.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] Resolute Forest Products became a member of the World Wildlife Fund’s Climate Saver’s Program on November 10, 2011 with a commitment to “reduce their absolute greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by 65 per cent by 2015 below 2000 levels” .
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] Resolute Forest Products has been criticized by Greenpeace and other organizations for advancing logging and road building in endangered species habitat in Québec and Ontario.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On 18 May 2010, Resolute Forest Products joined 29 other organizations including Greenpeace Canada and the David Suzuki Foundation to become a founding member of the Canadian Boreal Forest Agreement (CBFA).
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The agreement formalizes the members’ commitments to conserving vast areas of forests and enabling the legislated protection of large-scale areas that are needed to preserve threatened species such as woodland caribou.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] Claiming a lack of progress on delivering results within the CBFA, particularly on the creation of protected areas and caribou conservation plans, Greenpeace Canada and Canopy, two founding signatories, departed the agreement in December 2012 and April 2013 respectively.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] Greenpeace Canada released a report examining Resolute's sustainability claims in May 2013, alleging that the company is deceiving customers about the sustainability of their forestry operations and their interactions with communities, First Nations and workers.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] Greenpeace withdrew an earlier criticism of Resolute Forest Products on 19 March 2013 noting that a December 2012 campaign against the company “incorrectly stated that Resolute had breached the Canadian Boreal Forest Agreement”.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] On May 23, 2013, Resolute filed a $7,000,000 defamation lawsuit against Greenpeace Canada and two of its staff in Ontario Superior Court alleging the organization interfered with economic relations with their customers.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] In response Greenpeace launched a legal defense fund and characterized the lawsuit as a Strategic Lawsuit Against Public Participation (SLAPP).
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] In May 2016, Resolute filed a $300 million-dollar lawsuit in Atlanta, Georgia using the United States' RICO Act (which is primarily for fighting organized crime and racketeering) against Greenpeace.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] The petition's signatories are concerned that using RICO in this particular action is a legal attempt to stymie free speech.
[src:hydro-québec/abitibibowater] In 2019, the federal district court for the Northern District of California dismissed most of the claims by Resolute Forest Products and, in April 2022, the court ordered Resolute Forest Products to pay Greenpeace $800,000 in costs after Greenpeace brought an anti-SLAPP motion against the company.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The **Action démocratique du Québec** ([aksjɔ̃ demɔkʁatik dy kebɛk], lit.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] 'Democratic Action of Quebec'), commonly referred to as the **ADQ**, was a right-wing populist and conservative provincial political party in Quebec, Canada.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On the sovereignty question, it defined itself as autonomist; it had support from nationalists and federalists.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Its members were referred to as *adéquistes*, a name derived from the French pronunciation of the initials 'ADQ'.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The party was founded by dissidents of the Quebec Liberal Party who did not accept the Charlottetown Accord, and first contested the 1994 provincial election, electing Mario Dumont to the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Under longtime leader Dumont, the ADQ had a strong showing in the 2007 provincial election, reducing the ruling Quebec Liberal Party (PLQ) to a minority government and relegating the Parti Québécois (PQ) to third place.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ won 41 seats with 31% of the popular vote to serve as the Official Opposition in the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On 21 January 2012, the membership approved a merger with the Coalition Avenir Québec.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The merger was recognised by the Directeur général des élections du Québec on 14 February 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The party was formed in 1994 by a group of nationalists, known as *les allairistes*, that supported the Allaire Report, a document that advocated a decentralized federal system in which the provincial Government of Quebec would have significantly increased powers.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] After the failure of the Meech Lake Accord, which made many Québécois feel rejected by the rest of Canada, the Liberals adopted the Allaire Report as their constitutional policy.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] However, the party later chose the Charlottetown Accord over the Allaire Report in 1992.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The Charlottetown Accord would have recognized Quebec as a "distinct society" within Canada, but consisted of a much milder reform of the Canadian federal system.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] While most Liberals supported the Charlottetown Accord, a number of them opposed it and quit the party.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Led by Jean Allaire, an attorney from Laval and author of the Allaire Report, and Mario Dumont, a rising political star who had been President of the Liberal Youth Commission, the dissidents founded the ADQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Allaire became the first party leader, but resigned within a few months for health reasons.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] He was succeeded by Mario Dumont, who retained the leadership until early 2009.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Shortly before the 1994 provincial election, Yvon Lafrance, a one-term Liberal backbencher who served under Premier Robert Bourassa, switched parties to join the ADQ, becoming the party's first sitting member of the legislature.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In the ensuing election campaign, Dumont took part in the televised leaders debate and was elected as an MNA, but could not expand his electoral support significantly enough to get other party members elected.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] For the next eight years, he was the ADQ's lone MNA.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In the 1995 Quebec referendum on the Parti Québécois government's proposals for sovereignty, Dumont campaigned for the "Yes" side, in favour of the sovereignty option.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] However, in subsequent election campaigns, he has promised a moratorium on the sovereignty question, which earned him accusations of not having a clear and honest stand on the constitution question.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Although Dumont was a very popular leader, support for the ADQ always lagged well behind him.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In fact, for many years, the ADQ tried to capitalize on Dumont's personal popularity by using the official name *Action démocratique du Québec-Équipe Mario Dumont* (*Action démocratique du Québec-Team Mario Dumont*).
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In April and June 2002, voter dissatisfaction with both the Parti Québécois (PQ) government of Bernard Landry and the Liberal alternative presented by Jean Charest led the ADQ to an unexpected victory in a series of by-elections, bringing the party caucus to five members.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] After the by-election wins, the ADQ soared in popularity, leading the established parties in public opinion polling for the first time in its existence.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] For a brief period, a number of political analysts predicted that the ADQ could gather as much as 42% of the vote and more than 80 seats in the National Assembly, which would have been enough for a strong majority.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The increased popularity of the party provided the ADQ with larger grassroots support, more money and star candidates for the subsequent election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Dumont, who was able to recruit Beauce businessman Marcel Dutil, chairman of Groupe Canam Inc. as director of the ADQ's fund-raising activities, was considered as a serious candidate for the office of Premier of Quebec for the first time.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] As a result of the ADQ attaining greater popular support, its political opponents conducted negative campaigning against the ADQ for the first time.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Those efforts were successful in damaging the public perception of the party.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Moreover, the party's repeated backtracking on its various policies, including a flat rate income tax of 20 per cent, may have appeared opportunist and harmed the party's image as a viable alternative.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] It was also revealed that a close advisor of Mario Dumont had a criminal record, which prompted the media to question Dumont's judgment.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Dumont did not make any major mistake during the televised leaders' debate, but did not deliver the outstanding performance he needed to gain momentum.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] By contrast, Quebec Liberal leader Jean Charest was able to put Bernard Landry of the Parti Québécois on the defensive.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ received 18% of the vote at the 2003 provincial election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] All ADQ incumbents and star candidates, except Dumont, were defeated.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The losses were compensated by the election of three new ADQ MNAs, who were still unknown at the provincial level but were well established in their communities.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ drew enough votes from previous PQ supporters to give the victory to Jean Charest's Liberals, but did not make a significant breakthrough in the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In the months that followed the election, the ADQ benefited from anger over the decision of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) not to renew the license of Quebec City radio station CHOI-FM.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Radio host Jeff Fillion urged listeners to vote for ADQ candidate Sylvain Légaré in a by-election for the local district of Vanier.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Légaré defended the station's freedom of speech and was elected on September 20, 2004, which raised the number of ADQ seats back to five.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] A few days later, the ADQ held a convention in Drummondville, where its members adopted the new constitutional position of the ADQ, which was labeled as *autonomist* without much precision on what it actually means.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] ADQ members also elected ex-Liberal minister Yvon Picotte as President of the ADQ, a job previously held by political analyst Guy Laforest.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In the January 2006 federal election, ten Conservative Members of Parliament were elected in Quebec, at the federal level.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Four of those newly elected federal Members of Parliament – Maxime Bernier, Steven Blaney, Jacques Gourde and Josée Verner – came from districts represented by ADQ members at the provincial level.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] All except Bernier were at one point ADQ activists.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Blaney was ADQ candidate in Beauce-Nord in 1998.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] This breakthrough prepared the ground the subsequent growth of the ADQ, which could rely on a number of supporters from the modest Conservatives' organization in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In May 2006, the ADQ held a general council (French: *conseil général*) in Granby, where Dumont brought up the subject of having the current federal Conservative government broach the subject of a new round of constitutional talks in order to get Quebec to finally sign the Constitution.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Embarrassing comments were made by party president Yvon Picotte about PQ Leader André Boisclair.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Boisclair had decided not to run in a by-election for the district of Sainte-Marie–Saint-Jacques in Montreal, the district where he lives and which includes Montreal's Gay Village.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Accusing Boisclair of being a coward, Picotte jokingly said that the riding would fit Boisclair, who is openly gay, like a glove (*comme un gant*).
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Many journalists criticized Picotte, saying his comment sounded homophobic.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In November 2006, the ADQ held its sixth party convention.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The next month, it adopted its platform for the 2007 election, entitled "A Plan A for Quebec" ("Un plan A pour le Québec") and defined its stance on the controversial reasonable accommodation debate, which was well received by a substantial number of voters.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] When the 2007 election campaign started, the ADQ was running only a few candidates with widespread name recognition and lacked the financial resources its rivals (especially the Liberals) had.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Marcel Dutil announced that even though he likes Dumont, he would vote strategically in favour of the Liberals.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] However, polls showed that the ADQ had the potential to significantly increase its representation in the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Dumont ran an effective campaign, unveiling one plank from his electoral platform every day and therefore benefiting from sustained attention from his opponents and the media.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Dumont's performance had its own setbacks, however, as it led to more scrutiny of the ADQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The Liberals criticized the ADQ's financial plan as vague and unrealistic, accusing Dumont of underestimating its total cost.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] According to them, the ADQ's promises totaled $6.3 billion rather than the $1.7 billion announced by Dumont.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Besides, many journalists accused the ADQ of being a one-man show.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Two candidates, who had made inappropriate comments, were dropped by the party from the election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On election day, the ADQ made a surprisingly strong showing.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] It took 21 seats from the Quebec Liberal Party and 15 seats from the PQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] All five ADQ incumbents were re-elected, for a total of 41 seats.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] (The election of so many legislators without prior parliamentary experience led cartoonist Serge Chapleau to portray the ADQ MNAs as elementary school kids with Dumont as their teacher.) The reigning Liberals were reduced to a minority government, with only 48 MNAs.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] For the first time, the ADQ received a plurality of the popular vote among Francophones and formed the official opposition.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Nonetheless, it failed to take a single seat on the island of Montreal, but it did come second in many of the city's ridings.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ MNAs and supporters met in Victoriaville in late September 2007 to detail the party's environmental policy.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Former PQ Cabinet Member Jean Garon, former Hydro-Québec CEO André Caillé and environmental activist Steven Guilbeault attended the convention.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Tom Pentefountas, a former ADQ candidate in the district of Nelligan in a 2004 by-election, succeeded Gilles Taillon as President of the party.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Pentefountas enjoys little name recognition among voters in general, but he is a member of the Greek community and lives in Montreal.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] ADQ supporters hope that his profile might facilitate the party's attempts to connect with these constituencies.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] During the year that followed the 2007 election, a number of ADQ members such as Éric Caire, Gilles Taillon and especially Sébastien Proulx emerged as effective and articulate legislators.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Nonetheless, according to journalist Gilbert Lavoie, the more experienced PQ caucus was better able to position itself as the best alternative to Jean Charest's Liberals.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Political observers made unflattering comments about the ADQ's performance, and political support for the party seemed to lose momentum again.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ suffered a major setback in 2008, losing four consecutive by-elections by substantial margins.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Its support did not exceed 15% in any of the districts at stake.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Furthermore, MNAs Pierre-Michel Auger and André Riedl, as well as power broker Yvon Picotte, switched political affiliation from ADQ to Liberal in October 2008.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] ADQ Leader Mario Dumont made no official endorsement in the 2008 federal election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] He said that he would vote Conservative, but claimed that his colleagues and party's supporters were free to support whoever they wanted.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] MNAs Pierre Gingras, Ginette Grandmont, Linda Lapointe, Lucie Leblanc and Sébastien Proulx campaigned on behalf of the Conservative Party of Canada's candidates.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Yet, the election provided no increase in membership for Quebec's Conservative delegation to Parliament.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Quebec premier Jean Charest subsequently called a snap election for December 8, 2008.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Polls indicated that the ADQ entered the campaign far behind the governing Liberals and the PQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The party was routed in this election, falling to seven seats, six of whom were incumbents.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] This was five seats short of official status in the legislature.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] While giving his concession speech, Dumont announced that he would not be the leader of his party for the subsequent election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] While political commentators wondered whether the ADQ would survive Dumont's departure, there were three candidates for the 2009 leadership election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On February 27, 2009, Sylvie Roy was named the interim leader of the party.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ candidate came in third place in a June 21, 2009 by-election to fill the Rivière-du-Loup seat that Dumont vacated when he resigned from the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Dumont had held the seat for 14 years; he had carried it in the 2008 provincial election with over 50% of the vote, compared to the less than 15% garnered by ADQ candidate Gilberte Côté.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The loss reduced the ADQ to six seats in the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In 2009, MNA Éric Caire, former MNA and former party president Gilles Taillon, and former MNA Christian Lévesque ran for the party leadership to succeed Dumont.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] MNA François Bonnardel also considered entering the contest, but decided to manage Taillon's campaign.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Myriam Taschereau, a former federal Conservative candidate, and director of communications in the Prime Minister's Office, had also declared she would run, but later withdrew and endorsed Caire.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On October 18, 2009, Taillon was elected leader on the second ballot by the slim margin of 50.03% of ballots cast, two votes more than runner-up Caire.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Lévesque had been eliminated after finishing third on the first ballot.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On November 6, 2009, Caire and supporter Marc Picard left the party, alleging that the party organization lacked transparency and that Taillon had a dictatorial style of leadership.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] They resigned from caucus to sit as independents.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] This reduced the size of the ADQ caucus to four seats in the National Assembly.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On November 10, 2009, 23 days after his election as party leader, Taillon announced a new leadership election, citing the party infighting and alleging irregularities in the party's financial affairs, dating back to 2003, which he had called in the Sûreté du Québec to investigate.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] It was later revealed that he never contacted the Sûreté du Québec.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] He then explained that he would remain the leader until the results of a new leadership election, in which he would not be a candidate.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Caire said he would not run again for the party leadership, adding "Mr.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Taillon has done irreparable damage to the ADQ...
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] I don't know how the party will recover from this.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] I can't see the party going through a second leadership race.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On November 19, 2009, the party executive acclaimed Gérard Deltell as the party's leader.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] After Deltell assumed the leadership, the party enjoyed a modest rebound, rising from 5% in the polls in spring 2010 to 15% by the end of the year, and enjoying a substantial lead in the Quebec City region.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The party maintained the level of support it had had in the 2008 election in the by-elections held in Saint-Laurent and Kamouraska-Temiscouata in fall 2010.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ held a convention on November 13, 2010, adopting a number of proposals dealing with democratic reform and anti-corruption measures.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Deltell received a 97% vote of confidence from the party membership and received considerable attention when, in his opening address, he referred to Premier Jean Charest as the "godfather of the Liberal family".
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Charest threatened legal action if the statement was not retracted.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Deltell refused to apologize or issue a retraction and no action was taken.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] After Deltell took over the leadership, the party recovered from its precarious position, to a solid 18 percent of support in the opinion polls.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ recovery was at the expense of the Liberals because of Charest's unpopularity; after that, Charest recovered, but the ADQ benefited from a loss of support for the PQ following the collapse of the Bloc Québécois on the federal stage and internal dissent.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] After former PQ minister François Legault established a new movement called the Coalition pour l'avenir du Québec in February 2011, as an alternative to the sovereignty movement, there were calls for the ADQ to merge with it because of their similar policies.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Polls suggested the new movement would win a plurality of seats at the next election with 35 percent, with the ADQ taking eight percent if they did not merge.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On 14 November 2011, Legault officially launched the movement as a new political party under the slightly modified name of Coalition Avenir Québec (CAQ).
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On December 14, 2011, the ADQ announced it had agreed to merge with the CAQ, pending final approval from the party membership.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On January 21, 2012, the ADQ membership approved the merger of their party with the CAQ, with 70% of the party membership voting to merge.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The remaining ADQ MNAs, all of which supported the merger, were expected to join the larger CAQ caucus in the National Assembly, increasing the CAQ caucus size to nine members and increasing the pressure on Charest to call an election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On 22 January 2012, the results of the mail-in vote were announced, with 70% of ADQ members approving the merger with the CAQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In mid-December, after the parties had agreed in principle to merge, two former ADQ MNAs who had left to sit as independents joined the CAQ.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The four MNAs where were still members of the ADQ at the party's dissolution–Deltell, Sylvie Roy, Janvier Grondin and Francois Bonnardel–joined the existing five person CAQ caucus which was made up of other former ADQ and PQ MNAs.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Deltell served as the CAQ's parliamentary leader until Legault returned to the legislature in 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] As of 2025, Bonnardel & Caire are the last parliamentary survivors of the ADQ; Bonnardel was elected in the ADQ's 2007 surge and joined Legault's cabinet when the CAQ won government at the 2018 election, while Caire joined the CAQ in 2011 after two years as an independent.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Caire will retire from the National Assembly at the 2026 election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ advocated liberal economics reforms, or neoliberalism, coupled with support for increased autonomy for Quebec deriving from Quebec nationalism.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] On the political spectrum of Quebec, the ADQ was to the political right of the Quebec Liberal Party and the Parti Québécois.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The ADQ advocated the autonomy of individuals, the autonomy of municipal governments, and the autonomy of Quebec within Canada.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] In later years, the ADQ abandoned a number of radical free market proposals, including issuing school vouchers to give parents the ability to pay for the education of their children at a school of their choice.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Furthermore, the ADQ's conservatism was not based on religious values.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Its strongest base was provided by Chaudière-Appalaches and Québec, the most conservative regions of Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The party's popularity also reached other predominantly French-speaking areas of the province, including Mauricie, Bas-Saint-Laurent, Centre-du-Québec and even Montérégie in the 2007 provincial election.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] However, the ADQ had more difficulty breaking through in Gaspésie–Îles-de-la-Madeleine, Outaouais and the more cosmopolitan urban districts of the Montreal area.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] Because of the polarization of the debate over constitution from 1970 to 1995, conservative voters often limited their choice between the Quebec Liberal Party or the Parti Québécois.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] The Youth Commission of the ADQ was created in August 1995.
[src:hydro-québec/action-démocratique-du-québec] General conventions (French: *congrès généraux*) were open to all card-carrying supporters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:hydro-québec/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He was the son of Eugène Godbout, agriculturalist and Liberal Member of the Legislative Assembly (MLA) from 1921 to 1923, and Marie-Louise Duret.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He studied at the Séminaire de Rimouski, the agricultural school of Sainte-Anne-de-la-Pocatière and the Massachusetts Agricultural College, in the U.S. state of Massachusetts.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He then became teacher at the Sainte-Anne-de-la-Pocatière agricultural school from 1918 to 1930.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He was an agronomist for the Ministry of Agriculture from 1922 to 1925.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout became a Member of the legislature for the district of L'Islet in the Chaudière-Appalaches region after he won a by-election without opposition on May 13, 1929.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He was re-elected in the 1931 and 1935 elections.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout was appointed to the Cabinet by Premier Alexandre Taschereau and served as Minister of Agriculture from November 27, 1930 to June 27, 1936.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Shortly after the 1935 election, Conservative Leader Maurice Duplessis, a rising star in Québec politics, forced Taschereau to call the Standing Committee on Public Accounts, which brought to light the existence of widespread corruption in the provincial government.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] The revelations made by the committee were embarrassing for several Liberal insiders.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] On June 11, 1936, less than a year after being put back in office, Taschereau resigned.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He recommended to Lieutenant Governor Ésioff-Léon Patenaude the names of Édouard Lacroix and Adélard Godbout for his successor as Premier.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] When offered to form government, Lacroix declined.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] The offer was then extended to Godbout, who accepted and took over Taschereau's job as Liberal Leader and Premier of Québec, with the support of federal Cabinet Members.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] An election was then called for August 1936.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout had remained untouched by the scandals.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] But despite Godbout's talks of "a new order" in an effort to distance himself from the Taschereau era, his first government lasted only two months, as his party suffered a humiliating defeat in the 1936 election.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Led by Duplessis, the recently created Union nationale was put in office.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout lost re-election in his own district of L'Islet.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He remained Liberal Leader after being reconfirmed at the 1938 party leadership convention, but T.-D.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Bouchard led the parliamentary wing of the party until the 1939 election.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] World War II created the opportunity that Godbout needed to make a political comeback.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] An early provincial general election was called in 1939 and federal Cabinet member Ernest Lapointe, the Quebec lieutenant of Prime Minister Mackenzie King, took the stump for Godbout guaranteeing that no one would face conscription if voters supported the Liberals.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Through the campaign, Godbout relentlessly repeated the formal promise: "The government will never declare military conscription.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] I undertake, on my honour, weighing each of my words, to leave my party and even to fight against it, if even one French Canadian, before the end of the hostilities in Europe, is mobilized against his will under a Liberal government." The Liberals went on to win the election with 70 out of 86 seats.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout formed his second government, where he would serve as Premier and as minister of Agriculture.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] While Premier of Québec, Godbout published an article entitled "Canada: Unity in Diversity" (1943) in the Council on Foreign Relations journal.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Under Godbout's premiership, the provincial government implemented a number of significant progressive legislations, laying the groundwork for the Quiet Revolution that would be implemented by the government of Premier Jean Lesage a couple of decades later.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In fact, the Liberal administration delivered many of the proposals made by Paul Gouin's Action libérale nationale in 1935.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] 5. the nationalization of the Montreal Light, Heat & Power Company, a private corporation who had a monopoly on gas and electric light in the Montreal area, which led to the creation of Hydro-Québec in 1944.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Because he served during wartime and dealt with Dominion (federal) politicians who believed in a strong Dominion government, Godbout was forced to abandon a number of traditional provincial jurisdictions.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] 2. the power to tax the income of individuals and corporations, in exchange for a much more modest financial compensation from the federal government.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In a 1942 plebiscite, Canadian voters were asked to release the federal government from its commitment made to the Québec voters not to declare military conscription.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] While the majority of predominantly French-speaking Québec refused to support such a release, English-speakers throughout Canada mostly did support it.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Even though not that many people were forced to serve until the end of the war, the decision made by Mackenzie King to allow conscription (when both he and Godbout had specifically ruled out conscription earlier) was very unpopular in Québec.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Duplessis, criticised this and the federal encroachments on provincial autonomy, capitalizing on the Québec population's general mistrust of the federal government.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In the 1944 provincial election, Godbout's Liberals and Duplessis' Union Nationale received similar shares of the popular vote.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Although the Liberals got slightly more votes, the Union Nationale won a majority of seats in the legislature due to their strong support in rural areas.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Duplessis claimed that he would never take money from the Jews, and if were elected Premier again, he would stop this alleged plan to settle 100,000 Jewish refugees in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Through this story was entirely false, it was widely believed, sparking a surge of antisemitism that helped *Union Nationale* win.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Godbout served as Leader of the Opposition until the 1948 election.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Benefiting from post-war prosperity, the Union Nationale won an overwhelming majority.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] The Liberals won only eight seats, six of which were located on the Montreal Island.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Once again, Godbout narrowly lost re-election in his home district of L'Islet.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In 1950, he relinquished leadership of the Liberal Party to Georges-Émile Lapalme.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In 1949, Godbout was appointed to the Senate of Canada on the recommendation of Canadian Prime Minister Louis St.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] He remained a senator until his death in 1956.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Observers are divided about the significance of Godbout's legacy.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Lacking the oratory skills of Duplessis, his main political competitor, Godbout is sometimes judged very severely.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Federalists stress the importance progressive precedents that were set under Godbout's premiership.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] Autonomists on the other hand criticize him for taking a weak stance in the matters of the province's autonomy.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] More nuanced analyses claim that, being in power during World War II, he served in a difficult time, despite the shortcomings of his relations with the federal government.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] In his 2000 film entitled *Traître ou Patriote*, filmmaker Jacques Godbout, Adélard's nephew, lamented what he perceived as a lack of public knowledge about his uncle's work and premiership.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] On September 27, 2007, a former electrical power station in Montréal, at the corner of Wellington and Queen streets, known as Poste Central-1 was named in honour of Godbout in a ceremony attended by Premier Jean Charest.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] A bust of Godbout by sculptor Joseph-Émile Brunet (1893–1977) has been installed at the site.
[src:hydro-québec/adélard-godbout] For his contribution to the field of agriculture and the advancement of rural Quebec in general, Godbout was posthumously inducted to Canadian Agricultural Hall of Fame in 1962 and to the Agricultural Hall of Fame of Quebec in 1992.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It was established as a Crown corporation by the government of Quebec in 1944 from the expropriation of private firms.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This was followed by massive investment in hydro-electric projects like the James Bay Project.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Today, with 63 hydroelectric power stations, the combined output capacity is 37,370 megawatts.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Extra power is exported from the province and Hydro-Québec supplies 10 per cent of New England's power requirements.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company logo, a stylized "Q" fashioned out of a circle and a lightning bolt, was designed by Montreal-based design agency Gagnon/Valkus in 1960.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2023, it paid CA$2.47 billion in dividends to its sole shareholder, the Government of Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Its residential power rates are among the lowest in North America.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In Quebec, advocates for the creation of a public hydroelectric utility protested against high costs, poor rural electrification, and the lack of French speakers in management positions in hydroelectricity companies.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1944, Montreal Light, Heat & Power company was nationalised, along with its subsidiary, Beauharnois Power, and Hydro-Québec was created to manage the companies.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Quebec Premier Adélard Godbout adopted a policy of investing 10 million dollars per year in rural electrification.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] However, in 1944 the government changed, and the new premier Maurice Duplessis was opposed to any form of government intervention in the economy.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Local cooperatives were created to bring power to rural areas.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Duplessis remained in power until 1960, and during that time there were no further nationalisations of companies, and Hydro-Québec mostly served the Montreal area.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Between 1944 and 1962, Hydro-Québec's installed capacity increased from 616 to 3,661 MW while lowering residential power rates by half in the Montreal area.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Duplessis's conservative reign, now known as the Grande Noirceur, ended when he died in office in 1959.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The subsequent election of the Quebec Liberal Party, led by Jean Lesage, marked the beginning of the Quiet Revolution, a period of reform and modernization.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1962, the US government lent Quebec $300 million.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The funds were used to acquire independent power companies.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The new government gave Hydro-Québec an exclusive mandate to develop new sites.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1963 the government authorized it to acquire private electricity distributors, including the Gatineau Power Company and the Shawinigan Water & Power Company Hydro-Québec achieved province-wide scope.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] All of the 46 rural coops accepted Hydro-Québec's 1963 buyout offer, except Saint-Jean-Baptiste-de-Rouville which still exists.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1964, the Province of British Columbia provided the Province of Quebec with a $100 million loan. $60 million from that loan went to Hydro-Québec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The loan faced controversy in the Quebec legislature.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Because of the economic climate, demand for electricity dropped significantly in the early 1980s, which led to structural changes at Hydro-Québec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It became a joint stock company whose sole shareholder is Government of Québec, to which it pays an annual dividend.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It was also given the mandate to export power and to work in any energy-related field.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1986 the Quebec – New England Transmission began bringing power from the James Bay Project 1,100 kilometers (700 miles) south to the Boston area.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Phase II of the James Bay Project started in 1987 and took nine years to complete.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Construction of the Denis-Perron Dam began in 1994.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Like its counterparts in the North American utility industry, Hydro-Québec was reorganized in the late 1990s to comply with electricity deregulation in the United States.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The transmission division, TransÉnergie, was the first to be spun off in 1997, in response to the U.S.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's publication of Order 888.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Federal Energy Regulatory Commission granted Hydro-Québec a licence to sell wholesale electricity at market prices, enabling Hydro-Québec to expand its market.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec also acquired a substantial share of Noverco, controller of natural gas distributor Énergir, to participate in that market in northeastern North America.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2002 the Agreement Respecting a New Relationship Between the Cree Nation and the Government of Quebec between the Grand Council of the Crees and the Quebec government made possible the development of the Eastmain Reservoir.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The Eastmain-1-A and Sarcelle powerhouses and Rupert River diversion project were completed for $5,000 million CAD.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This will provide water power to the turbines at Eastmain-1, Eastmain-1-A and Sarcelle powerhouses and will provide increased flow at the existing La Grande-1 generating station as well as Robert-Bourassa and the La Grande-2-A generator stations.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1988, all of Quebec and parts of New England and New Brunswick lost power because of an equipment failure at a substation on the North Shore.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The March 1989 geomagnetic storm tripped circuit breakers on the transmission network causing a nine-hour Quebec-wide blackout.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In the North American ice storm of 1998, five days of freezing rain collapsed 600 kilometres (370 mi) of high voltage power lines and over 3,000 kilometres (1,900 mi) of medium and low voltage distribution lines in southern Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Up to 1.4 million customers were without power for up to five weeks.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec has created separate business units dealing with the generation, transmission, distribution and construction.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2017, production division generated 1.9B $ of net income (68.4%), transmission division 0.55B$ (19.4%), distribution division 0.33B $ (11.7%), and construction division did not generate any income.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Quebec redistributes all profits back to the government.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2017, the crown corporation contributed $4 billion to the Quebec government by means of net income ($2.8B), royalties ($0.7B), public utilities tax ($0.3B) and debt securities ($0.2B).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In the year 2000 with the adoption of Bill 116, which amended the *Act respecting the Régie de l'énergie*, to enact the functional separation of Hydro-Québec's various business units.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Order in council 1277-2001 specifies quantities to be delivered for each of the 8,760 hourly intervals, which vary from 11,420 to 34,342 MW.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] According to the 2017 annual report the workforce stood at 19,786 employees, both permanent and temporary workers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] And, a total of 1,304 employees were hired.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1981, the Parti Québécois government redefined Hydro-Québec's mission by modifying the terms of the *social pact* of 1944.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The government issued itself 43,741,090 shares worth C$100 each, and the amended statute stated that Hydro-Québec would now pay up to 75% of its net earnings in dividends.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This amendment to the *Hydro-Québec Act* started an episodic debate on whether Hydro-Québec should be fully or partially privatized.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Without going as far as Boyer and Garcia, Mario Dumont, the head of the Action démocratique du Québec, briefly discussed the possibility of selling a minority stake of Hydro-Québec during the 2008 election campaign.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] A Léger Marketing poll conducted in November 2008 found that a majority of Quebec respondents (53%) were opposed to his proposal to sell 7.5% of the company's equity to Quebec citizens and businesses, while 38% were in favour.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Lepage's talk show, former PQ Premier Jacques Parizeau estimated that such an idea would be quite unpopular in public opinion, adding that Hydro-Québec is often seen by Quebecers as a national success story and a source of pride.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This could explain why various privatization proposals in the past have received little public attention.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The liberal government has repeatedly stated that Hydro-Québec is not for sale.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Like many other economists, Yvan Allaire, from Montreal's Hautes études commerciales business school, advocate increased electricity rates as a way to increase the government's annual dividend without resorting to privatization.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Others, like columnist Bertrand Tremblay of Saguenay's *Le Quotidien*, claim that privatization would signal a drift to the days when Quebec's natural resources were sold in bulk to foreigners at ridiculously low prices.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] "For too long, Tremblay writes, Quebec was somewhat of a banana republic, almost giving away its forestry and water resources.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In turn, those foreign interests were exporting our jobs associated with the development of our natural resources with the complicity of local vultures".
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Left-wing academics, such as UQAM's Léo-Paul Lauzon and Gabriel Sainte-Marie, have claimed that privatization would be done at the expense of residential customers, who would pay much higher rates.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] They say that privatization would also be a betrayal of the social pact between the people and its government, and that the province would be short-selling itself by divesting of a choice asset for a minimal short term gain.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] On December 31, 2013, Hydro-Québec Production owned and operated 61 hydro plants —including 12 of over 1,000 MW capacity — with 26 major reservoirs.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] These facilities are located in 13 of Quebec's 430 watersheds, including the Saint Lawrence, Betsiamites, La Grande, Manicouagan, Ottawa, Outardes, and Saint-Maurice rivers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] These plants provide the bulk of electricity generated and sold by the company.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec's average generation cost was 2.11 cents per kWh in 2011.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company also purchases the bulk of the output of the 5,428-MW Churchill Falls generating station in Labrador, under a long-term contract that would be extended under a new agreement to 2075, if the agreement is ratified.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2009, Hydro-Québec bought the 60% stake owned by AbitibiBowater in the McCormick plant (335 MW), located at the mouth of the Manicouagan River near Baie-Comeau, for C$616 million.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2023, the energy sold by Hydro-Québec to its grid-connected customers in Quebec and exported to neighboring markets came almost exclusively from renewable sources.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro (98.53%) is by far the largest source, followed by wind (0.11%) and biomass, biogas and waste (0.01%).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2013, emissions of carbon dioxide (1,130 tonnes/TWh), sulfur dioxide (4 tonnes/TWh) and nitrogen oxides (10 tonnes/TWh) were between 49 and 238 times lower than the industry average in northeastern North America.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Imported electricity bought on the markets account for most of these emissions.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec's expertise at building and operating a very high voltage electrical grid spreading over long distances has long been recognized in the electrical industry.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] TransÉnergie, Hydro-Québec's transmission division, operates the largest electricity transmission network in North America.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It acts as the independent system operator and reliability coordinator for the Québec interconnection of the North American Electric Reliability Corporation system, and is part of the Northeast Power Coordinating Council (NPCC).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] TransÉnergie manages the flow of energy on the Quebec network and ensures non-discriminatory access to all participants involved in the wholesale market.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The non-discriminatory access policy allows a company such as Nalcor to sell some of its share of power from Churchill Falls and from other sources on the open market in the State of New York using TransÉnergie's network, upon payment of a transmission fee.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] TransÉnergie's high voltage network stretches over 33,630 km (20,900 mi), including 11,422 km (7,097 mi) of 765 and 735 kV lines, and a network of 514 substations.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It is connected to neighbouring Canadian provinces and the United States by 17 ties, with a maximum reception capacity of 10,850 MW and a maximum transmission capacity of 7,994 MW.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The TransÉnergie's network operates asynchronously from that of its neighbours on the Eastern Interconnection.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Although Quebec uses the same 60 hertz frequency as the rest of North America, its grid does not use the same phase as surrounding networks.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] TransÉnergie mainly relies on back to back HVDC converters to export or import electricity from other jurisdictions.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This feature of the Quebec network allowed Hydro-Québec to remain unscathed during the Northeast Blackout of August 14, 2003, with the exception of 5 hydro plants on the Ottawa River radially connected to the Ontario grid at the time.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] A new 1250-MW back to back HVDC tie has been commissioned at the Outaouais substation, in L'Ange-Gardien, near the Ontario border.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The new interconnection has been online since 2009 and the 315 kV line is fully operational since 2010.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] One drawback of the TransÉnergie network involves the long distances separating the generation sites and the main consumer markets.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] For instance, the Radisson substation links the James Bay project plants to the Nicolet station near Sainte-Eulalie, south of the Saint Lawrence, over 1,200 kilometres (750 mi) away.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2011, TransÉnergie invested C$1.3 billion in capital expenditures, including C$460 million to expand its network.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In addition to the new tie with Ontario, the company plans to build a new 1200-MW direct current link between the Des Cantons substation at Windsor, Quebec in Quebec's Eastern Townships and Deerfield, New Hampshire, with an HVDC converter terminal built at Franklin, New Hampshire.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The US segment of the US$1.1 billion line, would be built by *Northern Pass Transmission LLC*, a partnership between Northeast Utilities (75%) and NSTAR (25%).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In order to go ahead, the project must receive regulatory approval in Quebec and the United States.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The proposed transmission line could be in operation in 2015.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] According to Jim Robb, a senior executive from Northeast Utilities, New England could meet one third of its Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative commitments with the hydropower coming through this new power line alone.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec Distribution is in charge of retail sales to most customers in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It operates a network of 112,089 kilometres (69,649 mi) of medium and low voltage lines.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The division is the sole electric distributor across the province, with the exception of 9 municipal distribution networks — in Alma, Amos, Baie-Comeau, Coaticook, Joliette, Magog, Saguenay, Sherbrooke and Westmount—and the electric cooperative of Saint-Jean-Baptiste de Rouville.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec Distribution buys most of its power from the 165-TWh *heritage pool* provided by Hydro-Québec Production at 2.79¢/kWh.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The division usually purchases additional power by entering into long-term contracts after a public call for tenders.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] For shorter term needs, it also buys power from the neighboring systems at market prices.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] As a last resort, Hydro-Québec Production can also provide short-term relief.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Supply contracts above and beyond the heritage pool must be approved by the *Régie de l'énergie du Québec* and their costs are passed on to customers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The division signed one natural gas cogeneration agreement for 507 MW in 2003, three forest biomass deals (47.5 MW) in 2004 and 2005, and ten contracts for wind power (2,994 MW) in 2005 and 2008, all with private sector producers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It also signed two flexible contracts with Hydro-Québec Production (600 MW) in 2002.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec Distribution is also responsible for the production of power in remote communities not connected to the main power grid.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The division operates an off-grid hydroelectric dam serving communities on the Lower North Shore and 23 small diesel power plants in the Magdalen Islands, in Haute-Mauricie and in Nunavik.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In April 2011 the government of Quebec published a plan to encourage the adoption of electric vehicles, setting a target of 25% of cars sold in 2020 to be electric.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The plan also called for provincial utility company Hydro-Quebec to develop a strategy for the deployment of public charging infrastructure.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This resulted in the creation of "The Electric Circuit" (French: *Le Circuit Électrique*), the largest public network of charging stations for electric vehicles in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The first 30 charging stations were put into use in March 2012.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The network's first 400V fast charger was installed in 2013.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] As of 2023, The Electric Circuit offers almost 3,500 public charging stations in Quebec and eastern Ontario.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Usage is also compatible with the FLO and New Brunswick E-charge network adaptors.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec has made significant investments in research and development over the past 40 years.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In addition to funding university research, the company is the only electric utility in North America to operate its own large-scale research institute, L'Institut de recherche d'Hydro-Québec (IREQ).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Established by Lionel Boulet in 1967, the research centre is located in Varennes, a suburb on the South Shore of Montreal.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] IREQ operates on an annual research budget of approximately C$100 million and specializes in the areas of high voltage, mechanics and thermomechanics, network simulations and calibration.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Research conducted by scientists and engineers at IREQ has helped to extend the life of dams, improve water turbine performance, automate network management and increase the transmission capacity of high voltage power lines.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Another research centre, the *Laboratoire des technologies de l'énergie* (LTE) in Shawinigan, was opened in 1988 to adapt and develop new products while helping industrial customers improve their energy efficiency.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In the last 20 years, the institute has also conducted research and development work towards the electrification of ground transportation.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Current projects include battery materials, including innovative work on lithium iron phosphate and nano-titanate, improved electric drive trains and the effects of the large-scale deployment of electric vehicles on the power grid.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Projects focus on technologies to increase range, improve performance in cold weather and reduce charging time.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec has been criticized for not having taken advantage of some of its innovations.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] An electric wheel motor concept that struck a chord with Quebecers, first prototyped in 1994 by Pierre Couture, an engineer and physicist working at IREQ, is one of these.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The heir to the Couture wheel motor is now marketed by TM4 Electrodynamic Systems, a spin-off established in 1998 that has made deals with France's Dassault and Heuliez to develop an electric car, the Cleanova, of which prototypes were built in 2006.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec announced in early 2009 at the Montreal International Auto Show that its engine had been chosen by Tata Motors to equip a demonstration version of its Indica model, which will be road tested in Norway.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The Hydro-Québec Équipement division acts as the company's main contractor on major construction sites, with the exception of work conducted on the territory covered by the James Bay and Northern Quebec Agreement, which are assigned to the Société d'énergie de la Baie James subsidiary.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The construction of a complex of four hydroelectric generating stations on the Romaine River (1,550 MW) began on May 13, 2009.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The plants have been completed as of 2022 and have added a total of 1 550 MW of power.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In his March 2009 inaugural speech, Quebec Premier Jean Charest announced that his government intends to further develop the province's hydroelectric potential.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The call for further development of hydroelectric and other renewable generating capacity has been implemented in the company's 2009-2013 strategic plan, released on July 30, 2009.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec plans capacity upgrades at the Jean-Lesage (120 MW) and René-Lévesque (210 MW) stations and a third unit at the SM-3 plant (440 MW).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec first forays outside its borders began in 1978.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] A new subsidiary, Hydro-Québec International, was created to market the company's know-how abroad in the fields of distribution, generation and transmission of electricity.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The new venture leveraged the existing pool of expertise in the parent company.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It briefly held a 17% share in SENELEC, Senegal's electric utility, when the Senegalese government decided to sell part of the company to a consortium led by the French company Elyo, a subsidiary of Group Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux, in 1999.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The transaction was canceled in 2000 following the election of president Abdoulaye Wade.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Also in 1999, Hydro-Québec International acquired a 20% stake in the Meiya Power Company in China for C$83 million.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company held this participation until July 2004.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company's expertise was sought by several hydroelectric developers throughout the world, including the Three Gorges Dam, where Hydro's employees trained Chinese engineers in the fields of management, finance and dams.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec gradually withdrew from the international business between 2003 and 2006, and sold off all of its foreign investments for a profit.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Proceeds from these sales were paid to the government's Generations Fund, a trust fund set up by the province to alleviate the effect of public debt on future generations.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2022, Hydro-Québec, through its US Subsidiary HQI US Holding, acquired Great River Hydro, LLC. for the sum of US$2.2 billion.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The construction and operation of electric generation, transmission and distribution facilities has environmental effects.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydroelectric development affects the natural environment where facilities are built and on the people living in the area.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The development of new reservoirs increases the level of mercury in lakes and rivers, which works up the food chain.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] It temporarily increases the emission of greenhouse gases from reservoirs and contributes to shoreline erosion.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydroelectric facilities can transform the human environment.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Since the early 1970s, Hydro-Québec has been aware of the environmental externalities of its operations.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] To address environmental concerns, Hydro-Québec established an environmental protection committee in 1970 and an Environmental Management unit in September 1973.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Its mandate is to study and measure the environmental effects of the company, prepare impact assessment, and develop mitigation strategies for new and existing facilities, while conducting research projects in these areas, in cooperation with the scientific community.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In the late 1970s, the company set up a network of 27 monitoring stations to measure the effects of the James Bay Project which provide a wealth of data on northern environments.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The first 30 years of studies in the James Bay area have confirmed that mercury levels in fish increase by 3 to 6 times over the first 5 to 10 years after the flooding of a reservoir, but then gradually revert to their initial values after 20 to 30 years.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] These results confirm similar studies conducted elsewhere in Canada, the United States and Finland.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Research also found that it is possible to reduce human exposure to mercury even when fish constitutes a significant part of a population's diet.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Exposure risks can be mitigated without overly reducing the consumption of fish, simply by avoiding certain species and fishing spots.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The biological diversity of reservoir islands is comparable to other islands in the area and the reservoir drawdown zone is used by a variety of wildlife.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The population of migratory species of interest such as the caribou have increased to the point where the hunt has been expanded.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Emissions of greenhouse gases (GHG) rise significantly for a few years after reservoir impoundment, and then stabilize after 10 years to a level similar to that of surrounding lakes.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Gross GHG emissions of reservoirs in the James Bay area fluctuate around 30,000 tonnes of CO2 equivalent per TWh of generated power.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec claims its hydroelectric plants release 35 times less GHG than comparable gas-fired plants and 70 times less than coal-fired ones and that they constitute the "option with the best performance" overall.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Major environmental concerns relates to the human population of areas affected by hydroelectric development, specifically the Innu of the North Shore and the Cree and Inuit in Northern Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The hydroelectric developments of the last quarter of the 20th century have accelerated the settling process among Aboriginal populations that started in the 1950s.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Some native communities, particularly the Crees, have come to a point "where they increasingly resemble the industrialized society of the South", notes a Hydro-Québec report summarizing the research conducted in the area between 1970 and 2000.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The report adds that a similar phenomenon was observed after the construction of roads and hydroelectric plants near isolated communities in northern Canada and Scandinavia.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] However, growing social problems and rising unemployment have followed the end of the large construction projects in the 1990s.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The report concludes that future economic and social development in the area "will largely depend on the desire for cooperation among the various players".
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] After the strong rejection of the Suroît project and its subsequent cancellation in November 2004, Hydro-Québec, under the leadership of its new CEO Thierry Vandal, reaffirmed Hydro-Québec's commitment towards energy efficiency, hydropower and development of alternative energy.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Since then, Hydro-Québec regularly stresses three criteria for any new hydroelectric development undertaken by the company: projects must be cost effective, environmentally acceptable and well received by the communities.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec has also taken part in a series of sustainable development initiatives since the late 1980s.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Its approach is based on three principles: economic development, social development and environmental protection.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Since 2007 the company adheres to the Global Reporting Initiative, which governs the collection and publication of sustainability performance information.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company employs 250 professionals and managers in the environmental field and has implemented an ISO 14001-certified environmental management system.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The Innu Nation filed a $4 billion claim against Hydro-Québec in October 2020 to receive compensation for damages caused by the Churchill Falls Generating Station.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] At the end of 2010, Hydro-Québec served 4,060,195 customers grouped into three broad categories: residential and farm (D Rate), commercial and institutional (G Rate) and industrial (M and L rates).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The *Other* category includes public lighting systems and municipal distribution systems.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] About a dozen distribution rates are set annually by the *Régie de l'énergie* after public hearings.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Pricing is based on the cost of delivery, which includes the cost of supply and transmission, depreciation on fixed assets and provisions for the maintenance of facilities, customer growth and a profit margin.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Rates are uniform throughout Quebec and are based on consumer type and volume of consumption.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] All rates vary in block to mitigate any cross-subsidization effect between residential, commercial and industrial customers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec retail rates are among the lowest in North America.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] After a five-year rate freeze, between May 1, 1998 and January 1, 2004, the *Régie* granted rate increases on 8 occasions between 2004 and 2010 for a total of 18.4%.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] More recently, the regulator ordered two successive rate rollbacks in 2011 (0.4%) and 2012 (0.5%).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] However, rates are expected to go up by 3.7% a year from 2014 to 2018 to reflect a gradual increase of heritage pool electricity announced in the 2010 Quebec budget.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The average consumption of residential and agricultural customers is relatively high, at 16,857 kWh per year in 2011, because of the widespread use of electricity as the main source of space (77%) and water heating (90%).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec estimates that heating accounts for more than one half of the electricity demand in the residential sector.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This preference for electric heating makes electricity demand more unpredictable, but offers some environmental benefits.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Despite Quebec's very cold climate in winter, greenhouse gases emissions in the residential sector accounted for only 5.5% (4.65 Mt CO 2 eq.) of all emissions in Quebec in 2006.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Emissions from the residential sector in Quebec fell by 30% between 1990 and 2006.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Residential use of electricity fluctuates from one year to another, and is strongly correlated with the weather.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Contrary to the trend in neighboring networks, Hydro-Québec's system is winter-peaking.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] A new all-time consumption record was set on January 23, 2013 with a load of 38,910 MW.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Previous records were established on January 24, 2011 with 37,717 MW, on January 16, 2009, with a load of 37,230 MW, and on January 15, 2004 when peak reached 36,268 MW.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The price of electricity for residences and farms includes a 40.64¢ daily subscription fee, and two price levels depending on consumption.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The rates are all-included: power, transmission and distribution costs, but are subject to the Goods and Services Tax (GST) and the Quebec Sales Tax (QST).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] As of April 1, 2012, customers pay 5.32¢/kWh for the first 30 daily kWh, while the remainder is sold at 7.51¢/kWh.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The average monthly bill for a residential customer was approximately C$100 in 2008.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Electric meter readings are usually conducted every two months and bills are bimonthly.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] However, the company offers an optional *Equalized Payment Plan* allowing residential customers to pay their annual electricity costs in 12 monthly installments, based on past consumption patterns of the current customer address and the average temperature in that location.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2007, Hydro-Québec pulled out of a Canadian government initiative to install smart meters across the province, stating that it would be "too costly to deliver real savings".
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Since then, Hydro-Québec organized a 2-year pilot project, involving 2,000 customers in 4 cities, with time of use metering.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] A report, filed with the *Régie de l'énergie*, in the summer of 2010 concluded that the effect of marginal cost pricing with three levels of pricing in the winter would lead to minimal load and energy savings.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The company intends to gradually phase-in Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) between 2011 and 2017.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Early efforts will focus on meter data transfer, connect-disconnect, outage detection and theft reduction.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] For more than a century, industrial development in Quebec has been stimulated by the abundance of hydroelectric resources.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Energy represents a significant expenditure in the pulp and paper and aluminum sectors, two industries with long-standing traditions in Quebec.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2010, industrial customers purchased 68.4 TWh from Hydro-Québec, representing 40.4% of all electricity sold by the company on the domestic market.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The Quebec government uses low electricity rates to attract new business and consolidate existing jobs.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Despite its statutory obligation to sell electric power to every person who so requests, the province has reserved the right to grant large load allocations to companies on a case-by-case basis since 1974.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The threshold was set at 175 MW from 1987 to 2006 and was reduced to 50 MW in the government's 2006–2015 energy strategy.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Large industrial users pay a lower rate than the domestic and commercial customers, because of lower distribution costs.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2010, the largest industrial users, the *Rate L* customers, were paying an average of 4.66¢/kWh whereas companies with special contracts paid 3.07¢/kWh.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1987, Hydro-Québec and the Quebec government agreed to a series of controversial deals with aluminum giants Alcan and Alcoa.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] These risk sharing contracts set the price of electricity based on a series of factors, including aluminum world prices and the value of the Canadian dollar Those agreements are gradually being replaced by one based on published rates.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] On May 10, 2007, the Quebec government signed an agreement with Alcan.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The agreement, which is still in force despite the company's merger with Rio Tinto, renews the water rights concession on the Saguenay and Peribonka rivers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In exchange, Alcan has agreed to invest in its Quebec facilities and to maintain jobs and its corporate headquarters in Montreal.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] On December 19, 2008, Hydro-Québec and Alcoa signed a similar agreement.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This agreement, which expires in 2040, maintains the provision of electricity to Alcoa's three aluminum smelters in the province, located in Baie-Comeau, Bécancour and Deschambault-Grondines.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In addition, the deal will allow Alcoa to modernize the Baie-Comeau plant which will increase its production capacity by 110,000 tonnes a year, to a total of 548,000 tonnes.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Several economists, including Université Laval's Jean-Thomas Bernard and Gérard Bélanger, have challenged the government's strategy and argue that sales to large industrial customers are very costly to the Quebec economy.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] This argument is disputed by large industrial customers, who point out that data from 2000 to 2006 indicate that electricity exports prices get lower when quantities increase, and vice versa.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] "We find that the more we export, the less lucrative it gets", said Luc Boulanger, the head of the association representing Quebec's large industrial customers.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In his opinion, the high volatility of electricity markets and the transmission infrastructure physical limitations reduce the quantities of electricity that can be exported when prices are higher.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro Quebec gained attention with Bitcoin miners in 2018 after the crackdown on mining in China.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The province has an energy surplus equivalent to 10 Terawatt hours per year.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Hydro-Québec sells part of its surplus electricity to neighbouring systems in Canada and the United States under long-term contracts and transactions on the New England, New York and Ontario bulk energy markets.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2017, net exports revenues were at $1,651 million for a total of 34.4 TWh sent to New England (53%), New York (23%), Ontario (13%) and other (5%).
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Although most export sales are now short-term transactions, Hydro-Québec has entered into long-term export contracts in the past.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The corporation has 15 interconnections to neighboring markets.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 1990, the company signed a 328-MW deal with a group of 13 electric distributors in Vermont.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] On March 11, 2010, Vermont's two largest utilities, Green Mountain Power and Central Vermont Public Service, entered into a tentative 26-year deal with Hydro-Québec to purchase up to 225 MW of hydro power from 2012 to 2038.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The memorandum of understanding provides for a price smoothing mechanism shielding Vermont customers from market price spikes.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The deal is contingent upon the enactment designating large hydro as "renewable energy".
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] In 2015, Hydro-Quebec and the Ontario Independent Electricity System Operator (IESO) signed a 500-MW seasonal capacity sharing agreement.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Ontario has increased capacity in the Winter, and shortages in the summer.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Quebec has increased capacity in the summer, and shortages in the Winter.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Thus, the agreement serves as to achieve a cost-effective solution for both provinces.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Furthermore, in 2016 (IESO) and Hydro-Quebec signed a new long-term agreement starting in 2017 until 2023.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] The deal will send 2TWh per year to Ontario.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] On the other hand, Quebec should receive capacity from Ontario during Winter's peak demand.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] From 1944 to 1978, management of Hydro-Québec consisted of five commissioners, one of them acting as president.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] Their Bayesian network analysis suggests that increases in Quebec's hydroelectric capacity historically correlate more strongly with domestic demand and market price signals, rather than simply the availability of expanded transmission corridors.
[src:hydro-québec/hydro-québec] These findings can inform discussions of whether newly proposed U.S.–Canada intertie projects should include upstream reservoir development in environmental impact assessments.
